**The most common cause:** `Cannot read property 'X' of undefined`.

**Add this exact code at the VERY TOP of your main component**, right after the function declaration:

```jsx
// Put this at line 1 of your component:
if (!data) return <div>Feature loading...</div>;

// If you use an array:
if (!Array.isArray(items) || items.length === 0) return <div>No data yet</div>;

// If you have nested data:
if (!data || !data.user || !data.user.profile) return null;
```

**Pick ONE of those that matches what your component uses.** If you're passing `props.data`, use `props.data` instead of `data`.

**If you have no idea what variable:** Add this temporary debugging line at the top instead:
```jsx
console.log("PROPS:", props);
console.log("STATE:", useStateValue); // adjust if you use context/redux
return <div style={{border: '2px solid red', padding: '20px'}}>TEMP: Component is rendering</div>;
```

This will either show your data error in console OR prove the component renders (meaning CSS/CSS-in-JS broke it).

**Last resort:** Wrap entire component in Error Boundary:
```jsx
function DemoComponent() {
  try {
    // Your existing component logic here
  } catch (error) {
    return <div>Temporary fallback for demo</div>;
  }
}
```

**Literally copy-paste one of these.** Do not think, just paste and refresh.
